        'There\'s a word I want to introduce here because it\'s one of the most useful words in skill development and almost no one outside of a narrow academic field has heard of it.',
        'Enskilment.',
        'The anthropologist Tim Ingold borrowed it from phenomenology to describe the process of becoming skilled — not just learning about a domain but becoming someone who can inhabit it, move through it, read it, respond to it. He distinguished between two kinds of knowing: knowledge-about and knowledge-of.',
        'Knowledge-about is propositional. It can be stated, written down, transmitted verbally. You can learn it from a book. You can receive it in a lecture. It sits in the mind as information. This is what most formal education and most skill courses transmit. It has genuine value — you can\'t get far without it. But it is not skill.',
        'Knowledge-of — Ingold sometimes called it knowledge in the body, or knowing-in-place — is something else entirely. It is the lived capacity that comes from being in the practice, working in the environment, developing a relationship with the domain over time. It cannot be transmitted verbally. It cannot be written down in a way that gives you the thing itself rather than a description of it. You have to build it through direct engagement.',
