        'Let\'s be really specific. Let\'s stop talking about "perception" as a vague category and get concrete about what experts have built that gives them their advantage.',
        'The first thing is a richer perceptual vocabulary. They have more categories. Where a beginner sees "fast," an expert sees confident fast, nervous fast, reactive fast, mechanical fast — and each of those means something different about what\'s coming next and what to do. The categories aren\'t just conceptual — they\'re perceptual. When the expert encounters "nervous fast," something in them responds to it directly, before they\'ve consciously labeled it. The category is live, not archived.',
        'The second thing is predictive coupling. Expert perception is not just about the present moment — it\'s about what\'s coming. The expert perceives the early information that specifies the later event. In cricket, elite batters have been shown to initiate their movement before the ball is released, reading the bowler\'s body position to predict ball trajectory. They are not reacting to the ball. They are acting from earlier information that specifies what the ball will do.',
        'This is perception-action coupling — the idea that seeing and doing are not two sequential events but one integrated process. You don\'t see, then decide, then act. You see-act. The perception and the action are coupled, synchronized, fluid. And in the expert, this coupling has been tuned to pick up the earliest available signals — the most predictive information — which gives them what looks from the outside like supernatural reaction time or intuition.',
